# PROJECT ENGINEERING - UNIVERSAL FRONTEND ARCHITECTURE

> 🛡️ **FRONTEND SCOPE GUARDRAIL:** 
> - This rule ONLY applies to user interface elements, client-side state, styling, visual presentation, and edge BFF routing layers.
> - EXCLUDE heavy core backend business logic systems (which should reside in the dedicated backend repository).

Regardless of the framework (React, Next.js, Vue, Nuxt, Angular, Blazor), strictly adhere to modern frontend component-driven development principles:

## 1. COMPONENT SEPARATION (Smart vs. Dumb)
- **UI/Dumb Components:** Purely presentational elements (Buttons, Inputs, Cards). They receive data via props, emit events, and have NO dependencies on global state, API fetching, or complex business logic.
- **Feature/Smart Components:** Container components that handle business logic, interface with global state (Redux/Zustand/Pinia), perform API calls, and pass data down to UI components.

## 2. STATE LOGIC DECOUPLING & BFF BRIDGE
- NEVER write complex business logic, heavy data transformations, or direct API fetch calls directly inside a UI component's rendering block.
- **BFF / Server-Side Fetching Exception:** Full-stack frontend framework mechanisms (e.g., Next.js Server Components, Next.js Route Handlers/Server Actions, Nuxt Server Routes) are strictly allowed and encouraged to perform direct asynchronous data fetching for SSR/ISR optimization. 
- Keep these BFF routing layers as clean, lightweight orchestrators mapping requests directly to DTOs or external backend API services without standalone heavy architectures.
- Extract client-side state management and side effects into custom hooks/composition functions (for React/Vue) OR dedicated Service classes / State Containers (for Blazor/C# Dependency Injection).

## 3. STYLING & PERFORMANCE STANDARD
- Keep styling scalable (whether using Utility-first like Tailwind, CSS Modules, or SCSS). Avoid polluting global CSS.
- Ensure proper loading states (Skeletons/Spinners) and graceful error handling (Error Boundaries) for all asynchronous operations.
- Maintain base accessibility (a11y) standards: proper ARIA labels, alt text, and semantic HTML tags.
- Component Size & SEO: Aim to keep components under 150 lines of code; refactor into sub-components if exceeded. Prioritize semantic HTML and leverage framework-specific SEO/metadata APIs from the start.